The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, May 30, 2003  Business Briefs Mumbai, May 29:Thermax Ltd has posted  a 101 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 55.70 crore on a  consolidated basis for the financial year ended March 31,  2003, compared with Rs 27.62 crore during the previous fiscal.  The board of directors has recommended a 120 per cent dividend,  including a 50 per cent special dividend, for the year under  review. It has also recommended a bonus issue of 6 per cent  redeemable preference shares to shareholders in the ratio  of two preference shares (face value of Rs 10 each) for  every one equity share held.  New Delhi, May 29:The total import of  300 sensitive commodities jumped 20.8 per cent to Rs 13,236  crore during the fiscal ended March 31, 2003, compared with  Rs 10,956 crore in the previous year. A sharp rise in the  import of edible oil, which went up to Rs 8,458 crore from  Rs 6,476 crore in 2001-02, was the major factor contributing  to this spurt. Calcutta, May 29:Uco Bank has decided  to realign the interest rates on deposits and advances with  effect from June 2. The new rates on deposits with maturity  of two years and above would be 6 per cent, and more than  one year but less than two years would be 5.75 per cent. Haldia, May 29:Haldia Petrochemicals  Limited (HPL) today dispatched its first consignment of  polypropylene to Gail under the strategic marketing alliance  signed between the companies two months ago. Mumbai, May 29:The Rs 5,000-crore Videocon  group is set to acquire the technology for Asias first  tablet PC kind of device  PC Slate  for a consideration  of $ 2 million. Mumbai, May 29:UK-based Prudential Plc  has set up its fully-owned subsidiary, Prudential Process  Management Services, in the country at an investment of  $ 10 million. New Delhi, May 29:The government has  appointed A. K. Singh as the chairman of the Central Board  of Excise and Customs (CBEC) in place of M. K. Zutshi, who  will retire on May 31.
